NHANES Dataset Analysis

Introduction

The National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey (NHANES) is a large-scale, ongoing public health study conducted by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) in the United States [1]. Unlike many surveys that rely solely on self-reported questionnaires, NHANES integrates in-person interviews, physical examinations, and laboratory tests. This comprehensive design makes NHANES one of the most reliable and detailed sources of population-level health data worldwide.

NHANES collects a wide range of data, including demographic information, health questionnaires, physical measurements, and laboratory results. In this study, we focus on demographic and physical measurement data to explore the relationship between dietary energy intake, body mass index (BMI) [2], systolic blood pressure, diastolic blood pressure and total cholesterol levels among adults.

Analysis

At the first stage, it is necessary to identify the relevant fields in the datasets that will be used for the analysis. A range of data wrangling techniques is then applied, including data filtering, group-based aggregation, handling of missing values, and column transformations, to prepare a clean and consistent analytical dataset. Subsequently, the Bokeh library [3] is used to create interactive visualisations that support exploratory data analysis and facilitate interpretation of the results.

Fields In the Datasets

Demographics

Variable Description
SEQN Respondent sequence number
RIAGENDR Gender of the participant (1 = Male, 2 = Female)
RIDAGEYR Age in years at screening
RIDRETH3 Race/Hispanic origin w/ NH Asian
INDFMPIR Ratio of family income to poverty

Dietary

Variable Description
DR1TKCAL Energy (kcal)
DR1TPROT Protein (gm)
DR1TTFAT Total fat (gm)
DR1TCARB Carbohydrate (gm)
DR1TSUGR Total sugars (gm)
DR1TFIBE Dietary fiber (gm)

Body Measures

Variable Description
BMXBMI Body Mass Index (kg/m)
BMXWT Weight (kg)
BMXHT Standing Height (cm)

Blood Pressure

Variable Description
BPXOSY1 Systolic 1st oscillometric reading
BPXODI1 Diastolic 1st oscillometric reading

Laboratory

Variable Description
LBXTC Total Cholesterol (mg/dL)

Data Wrangling

  1. Load NHANES datasets
In[1]:
import pandas as pd

# 20172020 cycle
demo_17 = pd.read_sas("data/nhanes/2017-2020-P_DEMO.xpt")
diet_17 = pd.read_sas("data/nhanes/2017-2020-P_DR1TOT.XPT")
bmx_17  = pd.read_sas("data/nhanes/2017-2020-P_BMX.XPT")
bpx_17  = pd.read_sas("data/nhanes/2017-2020-P_BPXO.XPT")
chol_17 = pd.read_sas("data/nhanes/2017-2020-P_TCHOL.XPT")

# 20212023 cycle
demo_21 = pd.read_sas("data/nhanes/2021-2023-DEMO_L.xpt")
diet_21 = pd.read_sas("data/nhanes/2021-2023-DR1TOT_L.xpt")
bmx_21  = pd.read_sas("data/nhanes/2021-2023-BMX_L.xpt")
bpx_21  = pd.read_sas("data/nhanes/2021-2023-BPXO_L.xpt")
chol_21 = pd.read_sas("data/nhanes/2021-2023-TCHOL_L.xpt")

# Add survey year labels (representative year)
demo_17["Year"] = 2019
demo_21["Year"] = 2022
  1. Combine cycles and merge into a single dataframe
In[2]:
demo_all = pd.concat([demo_17, demo_21], ignore_index=True)
diet_all = pd.concat([diet_17, diet_21], ignore_index=True)
bmx_all  = pd.concat([bmx_17,  bmx_21],  ignore_index=True)
bpx_all  = pd.concat([bpx_17,  bpx_21],  ignore_index=True)
chol_all = pd.concat([chol_17, chol_21], ignore_index=True)

df = (
    demo_all
    .merge(diet_all, on="SEQN", how="inner")
    .merge(bmx_all,  on="SEQN", how="inner")
    .merge(bpx_all,  on="SEQN", how="inner")
    .merge(chol_all, on="SEQN", how="inner")
)
  1. Data cleaning and preprocessing
In[3]:
# Keep adults only
df = df[df["RIDAGEYR"] >= 18]

# Convert gender codes to labels
df["Gender"] = df["RIAGENDR"].map({1: "Male", 2: "Female"})

# Select variables required for analysis
vars_needed = [
    "Year", "SEQN", "Gender", "RIDAGEYR",
    "DR1TKCAL", "DR1TPROT", "DR1TTFAT", "DR1TCARB",
    "BMXBMI",
    "BPXOSY1", "BPXODI1",
    "LBXTC"
]


df = df[vars_needed].dropna()


# Remove implausible dietary energy values
df = df[(df["DR1TKCAL"] > 500) & (df["DR1TKCAL"] < 6000)]

# Convert Year to string (better for Bokeh widgets)
df["Year"] = df["Year"].astype(str)

# Add alpha column for interactive filtering
df["alpha"] = 0.4
  1. Summary statistics
In[4]:
from bokeh.plotting import figure, show
from bokeh.io import output_notebook
from bokeh.models import FactorRange
from bokeh.transform import factor_cmap

output_notebook()
Loading BokehJS ...
In[5]:
diet_year_gender = (
    df.groupby(["Year", "Gender"])["DR1TKCAL"]
      .mean()
      .reset_index()
)

# Create factor x values
x_factors = [
    (str(year), gender)
    for year, gender in zip(
        diet_year_gender["Year"],
        diet_year_gender["Gender"]
    )
]

diet_year_gender["x"] = x_factors

# Create figure with FactorRange
p_diet_year_gender = figure(
    title="Dietary Energy Intake by Year and Gender",
    x_range=FactorRange(*x_factors),
    x_axis_label="Year, Gender",
    y_axis_label="Dietary Energy Intake (kcal)"
)

# Plot bars
p_diet_year_gender.vbar(
    x="x",
    top="DR1TKCAL",
    width=0.8,
    source=diet_year_gender,
    fill_color=factor_cmap(
        "x",
        palette=["blue", "red"],
        factors=["Male", "Female"],
        start=1
    ),
    legend_field="Gender"
)

p_diet_year_gender.legend.location = "top_left"
p_diet_year_gender.xaxis.major_label_orientation = 1.0

show(p_diet_year_gender)

Conclusion: The figure shows that dietary energy intake for both males and females decreased from 2019 to 2022. Throughout this period, males consistently had a higher dietary energy intake than females.

In[6]:
bmi_year_gender = (
    df.groupby(["Year", "Gender"])
      .agg(mean_kcal=("DR1TKCAL", "mean"),
           mean_bmi=("BMXBMI", "mean"))
      .reset_index()
)

# Create factor x-axis values (Year, Gender)
x_factors = [
    (str(year), gender)
    for year, gender in zip(
        bmi_year_gender["Year"],
        bmi_year_gender["Gender"]
    )
]

bmi_year_gender["x"] = x_factors

# Create figure with FactorRange for grouped bars
p_bmi_year_gender = figure(
    title="Mean BMI by Year and Gender",
    x_range=FactorRange(*x_factors),
    x_axis_label="Year, Gender",
    y_axis_label="Mean BMI"
)

# Draw grouped bar chart
p_bmi_year_gender.vbar(
    x="x",
    top="mean_bmi",
    width=0.8,
    source=bmi_year_gender,
    fill_color=factor_cmap(
        "x",
        palette=["blue", "red"],
        factors=["Male", "Female"],
        start=1
    ),
    legend_field="Gender"
)

# Formatting
p_bmi_year_gender.legend.location = "top_left"
p_bmi_year_gender.xaxis.major_label_orientation = 1.0

show(p_bmi_year_gender)

Conclusion: From the figure, we can see that the mean BMI shows a slight decrease among females, while it remains stable among males.

In[7]:
bp_year_gender = (
    df.groupby(["Year", "Gender"])
      .agg(mean_kcal=("DR1TKCAL", "mean"),
           mean_sbp=("BPXOSY1", "mean"),
           mean_dbp=("BPXODI1", "mean"))
      .reset_index()
)

# Reshape data so SBP and DBP become separate categories
bp_long = pd.melt(
    bp_year_gender,
    id_vars=["Year", "Gender"],
    value_vars=["mean_sbp", "mean_dbp"],
    var_name="Measure",
    value_name="Value"
)

# Rename measures for clearer labels
bp_long["Measure"] = bp_long["Measure"].map({
    "mean_sbp": "SBP",
    "mean_dbp": "DBP"
})

# Create combined category: Gender + Measure
bp_long["Category"] = bp_long["Gender"] + " " + bp_long["Measure"]

# Create factor x-axis: (Year, Category)
x_factors = [
    (str(year), category)
    for year, category in zip(bp_long["Year"], bp_long["Category"])
]

bp_long["x"] = x_factors

# Create figure with FactorRange
p_bp_year_gender = figure(
    title="Mean SBP and DBP by Year and Gender",
    x_range=FactorRange(*x_factors),
    x_axis_label="Year, Gender and Blood Pressure Type",
    y_axis_label="Blood Pressure (mmHg)"
)

# Draw grouped bars
p_bp_year_gender.vbar(
    x="x",
    top="Value",
    width=0.8,
    source=bp_long,
    fill_color=factor_cmap(
        "x",
        palette=["#1f77b4", "#aec7e8", "#d62728", "#ff9896"],
        factors=["Male SBP", "Male DBP", "Female SBP", "Female DBP"],
        start=1
    ),
    legend_field="Category"
)

# Formatting
p_bp_year_gender.legend.location = "top_left"
p_bp_year_gender.legend.title = "Group"
p_bp_year_gender.xaxis.major_label_orientation = 1.0

show(p_bp_year_gender)

Conclusion: This figure shows that both systolic and diastolic blood pressure (SBP and DBP) remained stable for males and females between 2019 and 2022.

In[8]:
chol_year_gender = (
    df.groupby(["Year", "Gender"])
      .agg(mean_kcal=("DR1TKCAL", "mean"),
           mean_chol=("LBXTC", "mean"))
      .reset_index()
)


# Convert Year to string for categorical axis
chol_year_gender["Year"] = chol_year_gender["Year"].astype(str)

# Create factor x-axis (Year, Gender)
chol_year_gender["x"] = list(zip(chol_year_gender["Year"], chol_year_gender["Gender"]))

# Create figure with FactorRange
p_chol_year_gender = figure(
    title="Mean Cholesterol (LBXTC) by Year and Gender",
    x_range=FactorRange(*chol_year_gender["x"]),
    x_axis_label="Year",
    y_axis_label="Mean Cholesterol (mg/dL)"
)

# Plot grouped bars
p_chol_year_gender.vbar(
    x="x",
    top="mean_chol",
    width=0.8,
    source=chol_year_gender,
    fill_color=factor_cmap(
        "x",
        palette=["blue", "red"],
        factors=["Male", "Female"],
        start=1
    ),
    legend_field="Gender"
)

# Format legend
p_chol_year_gender.legend.location = "top_left"
p_chol_year_gender.xaxis.major_label_orientation = 1.0

show(p_chol_year_gender)

Conclusion: From this figure, we can see that mean cholesterol levels for both males and females remained stable from 2019 to 2022.

  1. Bokeh interactive visualisation
In[9]:
from bokeh.layouts import column, row
from bokeh.models import ColumnDataSource, Select, Slider, HoverTool, CustomJS, CDSView, BooleanFilter

source = ColumnDataSource(df)

# create initial filter (all True)
bool_filter = BooleanFilter([True] * len(df))
view = CDSView(filter=bool_filter)
In[10]:
# Interactive widgets
year_select = Select(
    title="Survey Year",
    value="All",
    options=["All"] + sorted(df["Year"].unique().tolist())
)

gender_select = Select(
    title="Gender",
    value="All",
    options=["All", "Male", "Female"]
)

energy_slider = Slider(
    title="Maximum Energy Intake (kcal)",
    start=500,
    end=6000,
    value=6000,
    step=100
)
In[11]:
# JavaScript callback
callback = CustomJS(
    args=dict(
        source=source,
        year=year_select,
        gender=gender_select,
        energy=energy_slider,
        bool_filter=bool_filter
    ),
    code="""
    const data = source.data;
    const yr = year.value;
    const g = gender.value;
    const emax = energy.value;
    console.log(yr)
    console.log(g)
    const N = data['DR1TKCAL'].length;
    const new_filter = [];

    for (let i = 0; i < N; i++) {
        let keep = true;

        if (yr !== "All" && data['Year'][i] !== yr)
            keep = false;

        if (g !== "All" && data['Gender'][i] !== g)
            keep = false;

        if (data['DR1TKCAL'][i] > emax)
            keep = false;

        new_filter.push(keep);
    }

    bool_filter.booleans = new_filter;
    source.change.emit();
    """
)

year_select.js_on_change("value", callback)
gender_select.js_on_change("value", callback)
energy_slider.js_on_change("value", callback)
In[12]:
# BMI scatter plot
p_bmi = figure(
    title="Dietary Energy Intake vs BMI",
    x_axis_label="Energy Intake (kcal)",
    y_axis_label="BMI",
    width=800,
    height=400
)

scatter_bmi = p_bmi.scatter(
    x="DR1TKCAL",
    y="BMXBMI",
    source=source,
    view=view,
    size=6,
    fill_alpha={"field": "alpha"}
)

p_bmi.add_tools(HoverTool(
    tooltips=[
        ("Gender", "@Gender"),
        ("Energy (kcal)", "@DR1TKCAL{0}"),
        ("BMI", "@BMXBMI{0.0}"),
        ("Year", "@Year")
    ]
))
In[13]:
show(
    column(
        row(year_select, gender_select, energy_slider),
        p_bmi
    )
)

Conclusion: From the figure, we can see that the female BMI distribution in 2019 is more concentrated compared to 2022. In contrast, the male BMI distribution in 2019 is slightly more spread out, but becomes more clustered in 2022. The most concentrated area occurs when energy intake is between 10003000 kcal and BMI is around 2040.

Conclusion

Overall, the distributions of BMI, blood pressure, and total cholesterol among Americans show noticeable changes between 2019 and 2022. BMI and blood pressure values generally became more concentrated over time, especially within the energy intake range of 10003000 kcal. For BMI, females show a more concentrated distribution while males become more clustered in 2022. For systolic and diastolic blood pressure, the majority of values fall within 100150 mmHg and 60100 mmHg, respectively, and males exhibit a wider spread with more outliers in 2022. In terms of total cholesterol, male values are more dispersed in 2022, whereas females remain concentrated around 100300 mg/dL within the same energy intake range. Overall, the most common pattern for Americans from 2019 to 2022 is that energy intake of 10003000 kcal is associated with moderate BMI, blood pressure, and total cholesterol levels, with females generally showing more concentrated distributions and males showing more variability.
